<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-490-372  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 490 372.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  May 28 1990 v24 n22 p6(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>GAO finds security slips. (General Accounting Office)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Anthes, Gary H.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The General Accounting Office (GAO) is finding federal agenciesthat are not complying with the 1987 Computer Security Act,therefore leaving some of the government's sensitive and mostimportant systems exposed to abuse, fraud, espionage and hackermisdoings.andP;  Congressmen say they will seek legal sanctions againstagencies that do not comply, including the cutoff of funds for newcomputer systems.andP;  Federal agencies have viewed the requirement ofsubmitting comprehensive computer security plans as a reportingrequirement rather than a useful management tool.andP;  Of the planssubmitted in 1989, only 55 of the planned 145 security controlshave been implemented, according to the GAO.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     United States. General Accounting OfficeData SecurityGovernment AgencyGovernment RegulationLegal Issues.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   (Implementation of security measures in federal agencies). (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>